00:00:21.670 --> 00:00:27.620
PROFESSOR: OK, so let me go
back to what we were doing.

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:30.090
The plan for today
is as follows.

00:00:30.090 --> 00:00:34.240
We're going to look at
this unitary time evolution

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:39.800
and calculate this operator
u, given the Hamiltonian.

00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:44.170
That will be the first
order of business today.

00:00:44.170 --> 00:00:46.660
Then we will look
at the Heisenberg

00:00:46.660 --> 00:00:50.090
picture of quantum mechanics.

00:00:50.090 --> 00:00:53.270
And the Heisenberg picture
of quantum mechanics

00:00:53.270 --> 00:00:57.140
is one where the operators,
the Schrodinger operators,

00:00:57.140 --> 00:00:59.510
acquire time dependence.

00:00:59.510 --> 00:01:07.480
And it's a pretty useful way of
seeing things, a pretty useful

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:11.620
way of calculating
things as well,

00:01:11.620 --> 00:01:16.360
and makes the relation between
classical mechanics and quantum

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:19.270
mechanics more obvious.

00:01:19.270 --> 00:01:22.530
So it's a very important tool.

00:01:22.530 --> 00:01:23.890
So we'll discuss that.

00:01:23.890 --> 00:01:27.020
We'll find the Heisenberg
equations of motion

00:01:27.020 --> 00:01:30.270
and solve them for a
particular case today.

00:01:30.270 --> 00:01:36.290
All this material is not so
to be covered in the test.

00:01:36.290 --> 00:01:38.740
The only part-- of course,
the first few things

00:01:38.740 --> 00:01:42.750
I will say today about solving
for the unitary operator

00:01:42.750 --> 00:01:46.770
you've done in other ways, and
I will do it again this time.

00:01:49.790 --> 00:01:53.510
So going back to what we
were saying last time,

00:01:53.510 --> 00:01:56.570
we postulated unitary
time evolution.

00:01:56.570 --> 00:02:06.300
We said that psi at t was given
by some operator U of t t0 psi

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:08.800
t0.

00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:12.170
And then we found
that this equation

00:02:12.170 --> 00:02:16.870
implied the Schrodinger
equation with a Hamiltonian

00:02:16.870 --> 00:02:21.480
given by the
following expression.

00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:32.830
ih dU dt of t t0
u dagger of t t0.

00:02:32.830 --> 00:02:36.740
So that was our derivation
of the Schrodinger equation.

00:02:36.740 --> 00:02:38.820
We start with the
time evolution.

00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:43.070
We found that, whenever we
declare that states evolve

00:02:43.070 --> 00:02:46.870
in time in that way, they
satisfy a first order time

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:51.230
differential equation
of the Schrodinger form

00:02:51.230 --> 00:02:56.491
in which the Hamiltonian
is given in terms of U

00:02:56.491 --> 00:02:58.240
by this equation.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:01.160
And we talked about
this operator.

00:03:01.160 --> 00:03:04.890
First we showed that it
doesn't depend really on t0.

00:03:04.890 --> 00:03:07.250
Then we showed that
it's Hermitian.

00:03:07.250 --> 00:03:09.430
It has units of energy.

00:03:09.430 --> 00:03:15.020
And as you may have seen
already in the notes,

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:18.610
there is a very
clear correspondence

00:03:18.610 --> 00:03:22.330
between this
operator and the way

00:03:22.330 --> 00:03:29.870
the dynamics follows with
the ideas of Poisson brackets

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:33.740
that are the precursors
of commutators

00:03:33.740 --> 00:03:35.480
from classical mechanics.

00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:37.040
So that's in the notes.

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:40.050
I will not go in detail in this.

00:03:40.050 --> 00:03:43.130
Many of you may have not
heard of Poisson brackets.

00:03:43.130 --> 00:03:46.880
It's an interesting
thing, and really that

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:48.680
will be good enough.

00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:53.180
So our goal today
is to find U given

00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:57.740
H, because as we mentioned
last time, for physics

00:03:57.740 --> 00:04:01.380
it is typically more
easy to invent a quantum

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:04.340
system by postulating
a Hamiltonian

00:04:04.340 --> 00:04:09.290
and then solving it than
postulating a time evolution

00:04:09.290 --> 00:04:10.180
operator.

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:24.270
So our goal in general is to
find U of t t0 given H of t.

00:04:26.820 --> 00:04:29.060
That's what we're
supposed to do.

00:04:29.060 --> 00:04:31.320
So the first thing
I'm going to do

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:34.510
is multiply this equation by u.

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:41.500
By multiplying this equation
by a u from the right,

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:50.110
I will write first this
term. ih dU dt of t t0

00:04:50.110 --> 00:04:55.012
is equal to H of t U of t t0.

00:04:57.610 --> 00:05:01.990
So I multiplied this
equation by u from the right.

00:05:01.990 --> 00:05:06.090
This operator is unitary,
so u dagger u is one.

00:05:06.090 --> 00:05:09.430
That's why this equation
cleaned up to this.

00:05:09.430 --> 00:05:13.420
Now there's no confusion
really here with derivatives,

00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:17.930
so I might this well write
them with normal derivatives.

00:05:17.930 --> 00:05:27.886
So I'll write this
equation as d dt of U t t0

00:05:27.886 --> 00:05:31.780
is equal to H of t U of t t0.

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:45.960
You should be able to
look at that equation

00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:50.230
and say I see the
Schrodinger equation there.

00:05:50.230 --> 00:05:51.930
How?

00:05:51.930 --> 00:05:59.720
Imagine that you have a psi
of t0 here, and you put it in.

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:06.730
Then the right hand side becomes
h and t acting on psi of t.

00:06:06.730 --> 00:06:14.110
And on the left hand
side, this psi of t0

00:06:14.110 --> 00:06:18.200
can be put inside the derivative
because it doesn't depend on t.

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:23.640
Therefore this becomes
ih bar d dt of psi of t.

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:29.530
So the Schrodinger
equation is there.

00:06:29.530 --> 00:06:31.850
OK so now let's solve this.

00:06:31.850 --> 00:06:33.680
We'll go through three cases.

00:06:33.680 --> 00:06:37.400
Case one, h is time independent.

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:48.480
So we're doing this
sort of quickly.

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:54.240
So H of t is really H like that.

00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:58.700
No explicit time
dependence there.

00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:00.510
So what do we have?

00:07:00.510 --> 00:07:02.730
ih bar.

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:13.210
Let's write dU dt
is equal H times U.

00:07:13.210 --> 00:07:18.020
And we tried to write a
solution of the form U

00:07:18.020 --> 00:07:24.630
use equal to e to the minus
iHt over h bar times U0.

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:32.600
Does that work?

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:40.030
Well, we can think du dt and ih.

00:07:40.030 --> 00:07:42.090
So we get ih.

00:07:42.090 --> 00:07:48.420
When I take dU dt, I have to
differentiate this exponential.

00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:53.530
And now in this exponential,
this full operator H is there.

00:07:53.530 --> 00:07:57.850
But we are differentiating
with respect to time.

00:07:57.850 --> 00:08:00.970
And H doesn't depend
on time, so this is not

00:08:00.970 --> 00:08:03.330
a very difficult situation.

00:08:03.330 --> 00:08:06.640
You could imagine the
power series expansion.

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:10.340
And H, as far as
this derivative goes,

00:08:10.340 --> 00:08:12.340
is like if it would
be even a number.

00:08:12.340 --> 00:08:15.200
It wouldn't make any
difference if it's an operator.

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:20.040
So the derivative with
respect to time of this thing

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:25.600
is minus iH over h times
the same exponential.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:38.159
Moreover, the position
of this h could be here,

00:08:38.159 --> 00:08:41.419
or it could be to the right.

00:08:41.419 --> 00:08:45.030
It cannot be to the
right of U0 though,

00:08:45.030 --> 00:08:49.630
because this is a matrix, a
constant matrix that we've put

00:08:49.630 --> 00:08:54.590
in here as a possible thing
for boundary condition.

00:08:54.590 --> 00:08:58.320
So so far we've taken
this derivative,

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:03.706
and then i's cancel, the h
bar cancels, and you get H.

00:09:03.706 --> 00:09:07.340
But this whole
thing is, again, U.

00:09:07.340 --> 00:09:10.940
So the equation has been solved.

00:09:10.940 --> 00:09:14.440
So try this.

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:15.630
And it works.

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:25.120
So having this solution
we can write, for example,

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:31.410
that U of t t0 is going
to be e to the minus

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:38.110
iHt over h bar, some
constant matrix.

00:09:38.110 --> 00:09:44.940
When t is equal to t0, this
matrix becomes the unit matrix.

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:51.180
So this is e to the minus
iHt0 over h bar times U0.

00:09:54.500 --> 00:09:59.140
And therefore from
here, U0 is the inverse

00:09:59.140 --> 00:10:06.520
of this matrix, which is nothing
else but e to the iHt0 over h

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:08.140
bar.

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:18.910
So I can substitute back
here what U0 is and finally

00:10:18.910 --> 00:10:31.170
obtain U of t t0 is e to the
minus iH over h bar t minus t0.

00:10:33.890 --> 00:10:41.180
And this is for h
time independent.

00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:43.900
And that's our solution.

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:46.435
There's very little
to add to this.

00:10:50.790 --> 00:10:53.710
We discussed that in
recitation on Thursday.

00:10:53.710 --> 00:10:56.560
This unitary operator
you've been seeing that

00:10:56.560 --> 00:10:59.420
from the beginning of
the course in some sense,

00:10:59.420 --> 00:11:02.800
that you evolve
energy eigenstate.

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:07.110
If this acts on any
energy eigenstate,

00:11:07.110 --> 00:11:13.380
h is an energy-- if you act
here on an energy eigenstate,

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:17.030
the energy eigenstate is an
eigenstate precisely for H,

00:11:17.030 --> 00:11:19.670
you can put just
the number here.

00:11:19.670 --> 00:11:26.700
That is e to the, say,
alpha h on a state psi

00:11:26.700 --> 00:11:38.290
n is equal to e to the
alpha en psi n if h on psi n

00:11:38.290 --> 00:11:43.110
is equal to en on psi n.

00:11:43.110 --> 00:11:48.910
So the function of an operator
acting on an eigenstate

00:11:48.910 --> 00:11:54.560
is just the function
evaluated at the eigenvalue.

00:11:54.560 --> 00:12:01.600
So this is a rule that you've
been using a really long time.

00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:05.140
OK, so when h is time
independent, that's what it is.

00:12:05.140 --> 00:12:10.110
How about when h has a
little time dependence?

00:12:10.110 --> 00:12:13.880
What do I call a
little time dependence?

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:19.590
A little time dependence
is an idea, the sign

00:12:19.590 --> 00:12:24.050
to make it possible for
you to solve the equation,

00:12:24.050 --> 00:12:26.800
even though it has
some time dependence.

00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:31.180
So you could have Hamiltonians
that are time dependent,

00:12:31.180 --> 00:12:33.870
but still have a
simplifying virtue.

00:12:33.870 --> 00:12:40.290
So H of t is time dependent.

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:54.655
But assume that H at t1 and h
at t2 commute for all t1 and t2.

00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:00.140
So what could that be?

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:03.890
For example, you know that the
particle in a magnetic field,

00:13:03.890 --> 00:13:15.435
the spin in a magnetic field
is minus gamma B dot the spin.

00:13:18.210 --> 00:13:24.970
And you could have a time
dependent magnetic field, B

00:13:24.970 --> 00:13:28.380
of t times the spin.

00:13:28.380 --> 00:13:30.680
I'm not sure this is the
constant gamma that they

00:13:30.680 --> 00:13:35.570
usually call gamma,
but it may be.

00:13:35.570 --> 00:13:41.500
Now then if the magnetic field
is time dependent, but imagine

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:46.350
its direction is
not time dependent.

00:13:46.350 --> 00:13:51.690
So if its direction is not time
dependent, then, for example,

00:13:51.690 --> 00:13:59.450
you would have here minus
gamma Bz of t times Sz.

00:13:59.450 --> 00:14:02.250
And the Hamiltonian at
different times commute

00:14:02.250 --> 00:14:06.260
because Sz commutes with itself,
and the fact that it's time

00:14:06.260 --> 00:14:12.770
independent doesn't
make it fail to commute.

00:14:12.770 --> 00:14:17.900
So if you have a magnetic field
that is fixed in one direction

00:14:17.900 --> 00:14:21.330
but change in time, you
can have a situation where

00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:24.370
your Hamiltonian
is time dependent,

00:14:24.370 --> 00:14:26.970
but still at different
times it commutes.

00:14:26.970 --> 00:14:30.640
And you will discuss such
case because it's interesting.

00:14:30.640 --> 00:14:34.290
But later on as we do
nuclear magnetic resonance,

00:14:34.290 --> 00:14:36.550
we will have the
more interesting case

00:14:36.550 --> 00:14:41.400
in which a magnetic field
rotates and therefore it's

00:14:41.400 --> 00:14:43.900
not that simple.

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:49.540
So what happens if you have a
time dependent Hamiltonian that

00:14:49.540 --> 00:14:51.560
actually commutes?

00:14:51.560 --> 00:14:56.780
Well, the claim
is that U of t t0

00:14:56.780 --> 00:15:02.660
is given by a natural extension
of what we had before.

00:15:02.660 --> 00:15:08.000
You would want to put
exponential of minus iHt,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.880
but the reason this worked
was because the derivative

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:15.880
with respect to time brought
down an iH over h bar.

00:15:15.880 --> 00:15:24.140
So one way to fix this is to
put t t0 H of t prime dt prime.

00:15:28.980 --> 00:15:34.635
So this is an
answer to try this.

00:15:39.760 --> 00:15:40.630
Look at this.

00:15:40.630 --> 00:15:44.810
If the Hamiltonian were
to be time independent,

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:46.520
you could take it out.

00:15:46.520 --> 00:15:48.480
And then you would
get t minus t0.

00:15:48.480 --> 00:15:53.390
That brings you back to this
case, so this looks reasonable.

00:15:53.390 --> 00:15:58.280
So let me call this
quantity R of t.

00:16:01.030 --> 00:16:05.660
And then you notice
that R dot of t,

00:16:05.660 --> 00:16:10.050
the derivative of this
quantity with respect to time.

00:16:10.050 --> 00:16:14.090
Well, when you differentiate
an integral the upper argument,

00:16:14.090 --> 00:16:16.460
you get just the
integrand evaluated

00:16:16.460 --> 00:16:21.350
at the time represented
by the upper argument

00:16:21.350 --> 00:16:24.140
of the upper limit
of integration.

00:16:24.140 --> 00:16:26.645
So this is H of t.

00:16:29.610 --> 00:16:36.370
And now here comes
a crucial point.

00:16:36.370 --> 00:16:38.900
You're trying to differentiate.

00:16:38.900 --> 00:16:43.580
This U is really e
to the R. And you're

00:16:43.580 --> 00:16:49.910
trying to differentiate to see
if the equation holds dU dt.

00:16:49.910 --> 00:16:51.480
So what is the dU dt?

00:16:55.960 --> 00:17:05.897
Would be d dt of 1 plus R
plus RR plus 1 3 factor RRR.

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:15.520
And now what happens?

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:23.280
You differentiate here, and
the first term is R dot.

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:29.520
Here You, would have one
half R dot R plus R R dot.

00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:39.480
And then 1 over 3 factorial,
but three factors.

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:46.910
R dot RR plus R R
dot R plus RR R dot.

00:17:53.900 --> 00:17:58.720
But here is the
claim R dot commutes

00:17:58.720 --> 00:18:09.050
with R. Claim R
dot and R commute.

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:10.470
Why is that?

00:18:10.470 --> 00:18:16.320
Well, R dot depends on
H. And R is an integral

00:18:16.320 --> 00:18:19.850
of H as well, but the H
at different times commute

00:18:19.850 --> 00:18:22.610
anyway, so this must be true.

00:18:22.610 --> 00:18:25.250
There's no place where you
can get a contribution,

00:18:25.250 --> 00:18:30.100
because R dot is like an H,
and here's an integral of H.

00:18:30.100 --> 00:18:34.270
So since the Hamiltonians
are assumed to commute,

00:18:34.270 --> 00:18:38.470
R dot commutes with
R. And this becomes

00:18:38.470 --> 00:18:41.820
like a normal derivative of
an exponential in which you

00:18:41.820 --> 00:18:45.840
can move the R dot to
the left everywhere.

00:18:45.840 --> 00:18:48.270
And you're differentiating
the usual thing.

00:18:48.270 --> 00:18:59.240
So this is R dot and times
the exponential of R.

00:18:59.240 --> 00:19:01.800
So actually that
means that we've

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:07.010
got pretty much our answer,
because R dot is minus

00:19:07.010 --> 00:19:11.300
i over h bar H of t.

00:19:11.300 --> 00:19:17.810
And e to the R is U,
so we got dU dt equals

00:19:17.810 --> 00:19:21.330
this, which is the
same as this equation.

00:19:34.430 --> 00:19:39.140
The only reason a derivative
with respect to time will not

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:45.880
give the usual thing is if
R and R dot fail to commute,

00:19:45.880 --> 00:19:46.790
and they don't.

00:19:46.790 --> 00:19:48.810
So you could put the R dot here.

00:19:48.810 --> 00:19:50.840
You can put R dot
on the other side,

00:19:50.840 --> 00:19:54.660
because it commutes with
R, but it's better here.

00:19:54.660 --> 00:20:01.800
And therefore you've got
this very nice solution.

00:20:01.800 --> 00:20:04.650
So the solution is not that bad.

00:20:04.650 --> 00:20:09.790
Now finally, I want to discuss
for a second the general case.

00:20:12.710 --> 00:20:20.806
So that's case-- there was a
1, a 2, a 3 H of t general.

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:25.270
What can you do?

00:20:25.270 --> 00:20:28.570
Well, if H of t is
general, there's

00:20:28.570 --> 00:20:31.560
not too much you can do.

00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:34.350
You can write
something that will

00:20:34.350 --> 00:20:38.570
get you started doing
things, but it's not

00:20:38.570 --> 00:20:42.310
obviously terribly useful.

00:20:42.310 --> 00:20:45.060
But it's interesting
anyway that there's

00:20:45.060 --> 00:20:47.530
a way to write something
that makes sense.

00:20:47.530 --> 00:20:50.830
So here it is.

00:20:50.830 --> 00:20:52.450
U of t and t0.

00:20:52.450 --> 00:20:58.230
I'll write the answer
and explain how it looks,

00:20:58.230 --> 00:21:04.090
and then you will
see that it's OK.

00:21:04.090 --> 00:21:05.200
It's interesting.

00:21:05.200 --> 00:21:08.710
But it probably is not
the most practical way

00:21:08.710 --> 00:21:09.895
you can solve this problem.

00:21:15.310 --> 00:21:16.790
So here it is.

00:21:16.790 --> 00:21:19.680
There's an acronym
for this thing.

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:23.900
T it's called the time
ordered exponential.

00:21:23.900 --> 00:21:27.750
This operator does something
to the exponential function.

00:21:27.750 --> 00:21:29.470
So it's a definition.

00:21:29.470 --> 00:21:31.350
So I have to say what
this time ordered

00:21:31.350 --> 00:21:37.830
