01:02:53.650 --> 01:02:58.020
So what you realize from
this is that this thing,

01:02:58.020 --> 01:03:05.690
this implies Ah
commutes with Hh.

01:03:05.690 --> 01:03:12.260
And therefore by
point 1, by 1, you

01:03:12.260 --> 01:03:20.810
have to dAh dt is equal to 0.

01:03:20.810 --> 01:03:25.150
And this is nice, actually.

01:03:25.150 --> 01:03:32.530
The Heisenberg operator is
actually time independent.

01:03:32.530 --> 01:03:34.590
It just doesn't depend on time.

01:03:34.590 --> 01:03:39.230
So a Schrodinger operator,
it's a funny operator.

01:03:39.230 --> 01:03:41.020
It doesn't have time in there.

01:03:41.020 --> 01:03:47.790
It has X's, P's, spins, and
you don't know in general,

01:03:47.790 --> 01:03:52.530
if it's time independent
in the sense of conserve

01:03:52.530 --> 01:03:55.430
of expectation values.

01:03:55.430 --> 01:04:00.420
But whenever As
commutes with Hs,

01:04:00.420 --> 01:04:04.740
well, the expectation
values don't change in time.

01:04:04.740 --> 01:04:08.100
But as you know, this
d dt can be brought in,

01:04:08.100 --> 01:04:10.740
because the states are
not time dependent.

01:04:10.740 --> 01:04:14.420
So the fact that this
is 0 means the operator,

01:04:14.420 --> 01:04:18.810
Heisenberg operator, is
really time independent.

01:04:18.810 --> 01:04:22.710
Whenever you have a
Schrodinger operator, has no t,

01:04:22.710 --> 01:04:25.830
the Heisenberg one
can have a lot of t.

01:04:25.830 --> 01:04:29.460
But if the operator
is conserved,

01:04:29.460 --> 01:04:33.640
then the Heisenberg operator
will have no t's after all.

01:04:33.640 --> 01:04:37.260
It will really be conserved.

01:04:37.260 --> 01:04:42.640
So let's use our last 10
minutes to do an example

01:04:42.640 --> 01:04:46.140
and illustrate much of this.

01:04:46.140 --> 01:04:48.560
In the notes, there
will be three examples.

01:04:48.560 --> 01:04:51.860
I will do just one in lecture.

01:04:51.860 --> 01:04:56.580
You can do the other ones
in recitation next week.

01:04:56.580 --> 01:05:00.495
There's no need really
that you study these things

01:05:00.495 --> 01:05:01.990
at this moment.

01:05:01.990 --> 01:05:05.410
Just try to get whatever you
can now from the lecture,

01:05:05.410 --> 01:05:09.840
and next week you'll
go back to this.

01:05:09.840 --> 01:05:13.050
So the example is the
harmonic oscillator.

01:05:21.080 --> 01:05:25.130
And it will illustrate the
ideas very nicely, I think.

01:05:25.130 --> 01:05:28.420
The Schrodinger
Hamiltonian is p squared

01:05:28.420 --> 01:05:35.400
over 2m plus 1/2 m omega
squared x hat squared.

01:05:35.400 --> 01:05:41.350
OK, I could put x Schrodinger
and p Schrodinger, but that

01:05:41.350 --> 01:05:43.880
would be just far
too much. x and p

01:05:43.880 --> 01:05:46.380
are the operators
you've always known.

01:05:46.380 --> 01:05:48.470
They are Schrodinger operators.

01:05:48.470 --> 01:05:51.980
So we leave them like that.

01:05:51.980 --> 01:05:57.150
Now I have to write the
Heisenberg Hamiltonian.

01:05:57.150 --> 01:06:00.490
Well, what is the
Heisenberg Hamiltonian?

01:06:07.540 --> 01:06:08.520
yes?

01:06:08.520 --> 01:06:09.852
AUDIENCE: It's identical.

01:06:09.852 --> 01:06:10.560
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

01:06:10.560 --> 01:06:12.140
AUDIENCE: It's identical.

01:06:12.140 --> 01:06:14.800
PROFESSOR: Identical, yes.

01:06:14.800 --> 01:06:18.280
But I will leave that
for a little later.

01:06:18.280 --> 01:06:21.670
I will just assume,
well, I'm supposed

01:06:21.670 --> 01:06:26.340
to do U dagger U.
As you said, this

01:06:26.340 --> 01:06:28.000
is a time independent
Hamiltonian.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:29.960
It better be the
same, but it will

01:06:29.960 --> 01:06:35.000
be clearer if we now write
what it should be in general.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:37.650
Have a U dagger and
a U from the right.

01:06:37.650 --> 01:06:43.550
They come here, and they turn
this into P Heisenberg over 2m

01:06:43.550 --> 01:06:47.380
plus 1/2 m omega
squared x Heisenberg.

01:06:50.300 --> 01:06:55.100
OK, that's your
Heisenberg Hamiltonian.

01:06:55.100 --> 01:06:58.660
And we will check, in fact,
that it's time independent.

01:06:58.660 --> 01:07:09.130
So how about the operators X
Heisenberg and P Heisenberg.

01:07:09.130 --> 01:07:10.810
What are they?

01:07:10.810 --> 01:07:13.040
Well, I don't know
how to get them,

01:07:13.040 --> 01:07:16.240
unless I do this
sort of U thing.

01:07:16.240 --> 01:07:22.170
That doesn't look too bad
but certainly would be messy.

01:07:22.170 --> 01:07:25.430
You would have to do
an exponential of e

01:07:25.430 --> 01:07:30.225
to the minus iHt over
t with the x operator

01:07:30.225 --> 01:07:31.990
and another exponential.

01:07:31.990 --> 01:07:34.290
Sounds a little complicated.

01:07:34.290 --> 01:07:41.150
So let's do it the way the
equations of the Heisenberg

01:07:41.150 --> 01:07:42.740
operators tell you.

01:07:42.740 --> 01:07:46.570
Well, X and P are time
independent Schrodinger

01:07:46.570 --> 01:07:49.950
operators, so that equation
that I boxed holds.

01:07:49.950 --> 01:07:57.290
So ih dx Heisenberg
dt is nothing else

01:07:57.290 --> 01:08:02.910
than X Heisenberg commuted
with H Heisenberg.

01:08:02.910 --> 01:08:05.860
OK, can we do that commutator?

01:08:05.860 --> 01:08:07.030
Yes.

01:08:07.030 --> 01:08:09.580
Because X Heisenberg,
as you remember,

01:08:09.580 --> 01:08:11.670
just commutes with P Heisenberg.

01:08:11.670 --> 01:08:15.422
So instead of the
Hamiltonian, you can put this.

01:08:15.422 --> 01:08:20.720
This is X Heisenberg P
Heisenberg squared over 2m.

01:08:27.352 --> 01:08:30.330
OK well, X Heisenberg
P Heisenberg

01:08:30.330 --> 01:08:34.240
is like you had X and P.
So what is this commutator?

01:08:34.240 --> 01:08:36.200
You probably know it by now.

01:08:36.200 --> 01:08:39.600
You act with this
and these two p.

01:08:39.600 --> 01:08:43.350
So it acts on one, acts on the
other, gives the same on each.

01:08:43.350 --> 01:08:49.100
So you get P Heisenberg times
the commutator of X and P,

01:08:49.100 --> 01:08:53.830
which is ih bar
times a factor of 2.

01:08:57.250 --> 01:09:00.760
So we could put hats.

01:09:00.760 --> 01:09:03.689
Better maybe.

01:09:03.689 --> 01:09:05.960
And then what do we get?

01:09:05.960 --> 01:09:09.069
The ih there and ih cancels.

01:09:09.069 --> 01:09:11.029
And we get some
nice equation that

01:09:11.029 --> 01:09:17.960
says dX Heisenberg dt is
1 over m P Heisenberg.

01:09:21.430 --> 01:09:23.729
Well, it actually
looks like an equation

01:09:23.729 --> 01:09:25.310
in classical mechanics.

01:09:25.310 --> 01:09:28.109
dx dt is P over m.

01:09:28.109 --> 01:09:31.529
So that's a good thing about the
Heisenberg equations of motion.

01:09:31.529 --> 01:09:34.960
They look like
ordinary equations

01:09:34.960 --> 01:09:37.890
for dynamical variables.

01:09:37.890 --> 01:09:39.560
Well, we've got this one.

01:09:39.560 --> 01:09:46.479
Let's get P. Well, we didn't
get the operator still,

01:09:46.479 --> 01:09:49.569
but we got an equation.

01:09:49.569 --> 01:09:53.100
So how about P dP dt.

01:09:53.100 --> 01:10:03.060
So ih dP Heisenberg dt would be
P Heisenberg with H Heisenberg.

01:10:03.060 --> 01:10:06.550
And this time only the
potential term in here matters.

01:10:06.550 --> 01:10:11.090
So it's P Heisenberg
with 1/2 m omega

01:10:11.090 --> 01:10:14.730
squared X Heisenberg squared.

01:10:14.730 --> 01:10:15.695
So what do we?

01:10:15.695 --> 01:10:20.340
We get 1/2 m omega squared.

01:10:20.340 --> 01:10:23.870
Then we get again a factor of 2.

01:10:23.870 --> 01:10:27.420
Then we get one left over Xh.

01:10:27.420 --> 01:10:33.310
And then a P with Xh,
which is a minus ih bar.

01:10:33.310 --> 01:10:43.302
So the ih bars cancel, and we
get dPh dt is equal to-- the h

01:10:43.302 --> 01:10:48.380
bar cancelled-- m
omega squared Xh.

01:10:48.380 --> 01:10:49.250
Minus m.

01:10:56.960 --> 01:11:01.616
All right, so these are our
Heisenberg equations of motion.

01:11:04.570 --> 01:11:08.350
So how do we solve for them now?

01:11:08.350 --> 01:11:12.570
Well, you sort of have
to try the kind of things

01:11:12.570 --> 01:11:14.690
that you would do classically.

01:11:14.690 --> 01:11:18.140
Take a second derivative
of this equation.

01:11:18.140 --> 01:11:29.430
d second Xh dt squared
would be 1 over m dPh dt.

01:11:29.430 --> 01:11:32.550
And the dPh dt
would be [INAUDIBLE]

01:11:32.550 --> 01:11:39.530
1 over m times minus
m omega squared Xh.

01:11:39.530 --> 01:11:50.710
So d second Xh dt squared is
equal to minus omega squared

01:11:50.710 --> 01:11:55.420
Xh, exactly the
equation of motion

01:11:55.420 --> 01:11:57.050
of a harmonic oscillator.

01:12:01.010 --> 01:12:05.060
It's really absolutely
nice that you

01:12:05.060 --> 01:12:09.350
recover those equations
that you had before,

01:12:09.350 --> 01:12:14.310
except that now you're
talking operators.

01:12:14.310 --> 01:12:17.970
And it's going to simplify your
life quite dramatically when

01:12:17.970 --> 01:12:23.400
you try to use these
operators, because, in a sense,

01:12:23.400 --> 01:12:28.840
solving for the time
dependent Heisenberg operators

01:12:28.840 --> 01:12:33.340
is the same as finding the
time evolution of all states.

01:12:33.340 --> 01:12:35.730
This time the operators
change, and you

01:12:35.730 --> 01:12:38.020
will know what they change like.

01:12:38.020 --> 01:12:39.500
So you have this.

01:12:39.500 --> 01:12:48.120
And then you write Xh is equal
to A cosine omega t plus B

01:12:48.120 --> 01:12:54.910
sine omega t where A
and B are some time

01:12:54.910 --> 01:12:56.560
independent operators.

01:12:56.560 --> 01:13:04.360
So Xh of t, well,
that's a solution.

01:13:04.360 --> 01:13:07.880
How about what is P?

01:13:07.880 --> 01:13:18.590
Ph of t would be m dX m dx dt.

01:13:18.590 --> 01:13:31.190
So you get minus m omega
sine omega tA plus m omega

01:13:31.190 --> 01:13:33.100
cosine omega tB.

01:13:38.053 --> 01:13:40.480
OK, so that's it.

01:13:40.480 --> 01:13:42.210
That is the most
general solution.

01:13:44.780 --> 01:13:50.280
But it still doesn't look like
what you would want, does it?

01:13:50.280 --> 01:13:54.580
No, because you haven't used
the time equals 0 conditions.

01:13:54.580 --> 01:13:57.430
At time equals 0, the
Heisenberg operators

01:13:57.430 --> 01:14:00.310
are identical they to the
Schrodinger operators.

01:14:00.310 --> 01:14:09.070
So at t equals 0,
Xh of t becomes A,

01:14:09.070 --> 01:14:15.440
but that must be X hat,
the Schrodinger operator.

01:14:15.440 --> 01:14:21.630
And at t equals
0, Ph of t becomes

01:14:21.630 --> 01:14:30.880
equal to this is 0
m omega B. And that

01:14:30.880 --> 01:14:35.580
must be equal to
the P hat operator.

01:14:35.580 --> 01:14:43.220
So actually we have already
now A and B. So B from here

01:14:43.220 --> 01:14:47.890
is P hat over m omega.

01:14:47.890 --> 01:14:55.040
And therefore Xh
of t is equal to A,

01:14:55.040 --> 01:15:00.370
which is X hat cosine
omega t plus B, which

01:15:00.370 --> 01:15:06.560
is P hat over m
omega sine omega t.

01:15:06.560 --> 01:15:12.660
An Ph of t is here.

01:15:12.660 --> 01:15:23.780
A is-- Ph of t is m omega
B, which is [INAUDIBLE] P.

01:15:23.780 --> 01:15:33.563
So it's P hat cosine
omega t minus m omega X

01:15:33.563 --> 01:15:36.050
hat sine omega t.

01:15:42.640 --> 01:15:43.800
So let's see.

01:15:43.800 --> 01:15:46.380
I hope I didn't make mistakes.

01:15:46.380 --> 01:15:50.360
P hat minus m omega
X hat sine omega t.

01:15:50.360 --> 01:15:53.000
Yep, this is correct.

01:15:53.000 --> 01:15:59.400
This is your whole solution
for the Heisenberg operators.

01:15:59.400 --> 01:16:04.990
So any expectation value
of any power of X and P

01:16:04.990 --> 01:16:08.630
that you will want to
find its time dependence,

01:16:08.630 --> 01:16:11.490
just put those
Heisenberg operators,

01:16:11.490 --> 01:16:15.630
and you will calculate things
with states at time equals 0.

01:16:15.630 --> 01:16:18.360
It will become very easy.

01:16:18.360 --> 01:16:20.760
So the last thing
I want to do is

01:16:20.760 --> 01:16:26.730
complete the promise
that we had about what

01:16:26.730 --> 01:16:30.520
is the Heisenberg Hamiltonian.

01:16:30.520 --> 01:16:34.440
Well, we had the Heisenberg
Hamiltonian there.

01:16:34.440 --> 01:16:38.300
And now we know the
Heisenberg operators

01:16:38.300 --> 01:16:43.800
in terms of the Schrodinger one.

01:16:43.800 --> 01:16:53.630
So Hh of t is equal to
Ph-- 1/2m Ph squared.

01:16:53.630 --> 01:17:01.550
So I have P hat cosine omega t
minus m omega X hat sine omega

01:17:01.550 --> 01:17:15.120
t squared plus 1/2 m
omega squared Xh squared.

01:17:15.120 --> 01:17:19.940
So X hat cosine
omega t plus P hat

01:17:19.940 --> 01:17:27.150
over m omega sine
omega t squared.

01:17:27.150 --> 01:17:30.810
So that's what the
Heisenberg Hamiltonian is.

01:17:30.810 --> 01:17:36.010
So let's simplify this.

01:17:36.010 --> 01:17:37.790
Well, let's square these things.

01:17:37.790 --> 01:17:47.310
You have 1/2m cosine squared
omega t P hat squared.

01:17:47.310 --> 01:17:50.750
Let's do the square of this one.

01:17:50.750 --> 01:17:57.340
You would have
plus 1/2m m squared

01:17:57.340 --> 01:18:07.440
omega squared sine
squared omega t X squared.

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:12.340
And then we have
the cross product,

01:18:12.340 --> 01:18:17.465
which would be plus--
or actually minus 1/2m.

01:18:20.120 --> 01:18:22.910
The product of these two things.

01:18:22.910 --> 01:18:29.900
m omega sine omega
t cosine omega t.

01:18:29.900 --> 01:18:35.670
And you have Px plus XP.

01:18:35.670 --> 01:18:45.000
OK, I squared the first terms.

01:18:45.000 --> 01:18:46.410
Now the second one.

01:18:46.410 --> 01:18:49.120
Well, let's square
the P squared here.

01:18:49.120 --> 01:18:51.540
What do we have?

01:18:51.540 --> 01:18:57.950
1/2 m omega squared
over m squared

01:18:57.950 --> 01:19:06.120
omega squared sine squared
of omega t P squared.

01:19:06.120 --> 01:19:11.740
The x plus 1/2 m
omega squared cosine

01:19:11.740 --> 01:19:14.965
squared omega t X squared.

01:19:17.740 --> 01:19:20.880
And the cross term.

01:19:20.880 --> 01:19:37.990
Plus 1/2 m omega squared over
m omega times cosine omega t

01:19:37.990 --> 01:19:42.863
sine omega t XP plus PX.

01:19:45.540 --> 01:19:49.740
A little bit of work,
but what do we get?

01:19:49.740 --> 01:19:52.330
Well, 1/2 m.

01:19:52.330 --> 01:19:56.170
And here we must
have 1/2 m, correct.

01:19:56.170 --> 01:19:58.190
1/2 m.

01:19:58.190 --> 01:20:01.040
Sine squared omega t P squared.

01:20:01.040 --> 01:20:05.680
So this is equal
1/2 m P squared.

01:20:08.370 --> 01:20:14.180
These one's, hall here you
have 1/2 m omega squared.

01:20:14.180 --> 01:20:18.440
So it's 1/2 m omega
squared cosine and sine

01:20:18.440 --> 01:20:21.930
squared is X hat squared.

01:20:21.930 --> 01:20:26.430
And then here we have
all being over 2.

01:20:26.430 --> 01:20:30.970
And here omega over 2,
same factors, same factors,

01:20:30.970 --> 01:20:33.350
opposite signs.

01:20:33.350 --> 01:20:35.460
Very good.

01:20:35.460 --> 01:20:37.000
Schrodinger Hamiltonian.

01:20:37.000 --> 01:20:41.340
So you confirm that this
theoretical expectation

01:20:41.340 --> 01:20:43.350
is absolutely correct.

01:20:43.350 --> 01:20:45.100
And what's the meaning?

01:20:45.100 --> 01:20:47.900
You have the
Heisenberg Hamiltonian

01:20:47.900 --> 01:20:51.000
written in terms of the
Heisenberg variables.

01:20:51.000 --> 01:20:57.040
But by the time you substitute
these Heisenberg variables in,

01:20:57.040 --> 01:21:01.130
it just becomes identical to
the Schrodinger Hamiltonian.

